div.p:
1. At the outset of the discussion it was made clear by the Soviets that they would insist upon a minimal feeding standard for Austria. The following proposal with regard to foreight [foreign?] sources of food supply was made by me and supported by the British and French:
“The Allied Council for Austria is further unanimously agreed that, as a matter of policy, food to meet the Austrian deficit should come from normal prewar sources, principally Hungary, Rumania, Yugoslavia, Czechoslovakia and Bulgaria;
That an examination be made of the imports which present conditions in those countries will permit;
